text.tspan: USERS INPUT
Using innerHTML and className
allowed us to appendChild a lot of
markup to the DOM quickly in
order to get an overall feeling for
our App. This allows us to work
out the UX and UI of the design
after inital sketches in a real live
case study.
rapid prototypes allow your idea to be tested
without going to far into production
NAVIGATION
Keeping this prototype simple
while in development was a big
part of our strategy, sticking to a
two page app.
Using Sass variables
and nested selectors allows us to
be flexible with the layout in
testing, able to change things
globally very quickly.
GRABBING DATA
Using HTML5’s input tags and
javascripts ability to capture
values from the DOM we were
able to get the data we needed.
This allows this prototype to
append the information provided
into the users own library. This
data provides basic info like
average ratings and number of
books.
CREATING A WORKING PROTOTYPE
Creating interaction in a design without going all the way into a database can be
done through front end javascript or jQuery. This allows a hands on approach to
solving problems and how to continue asking questions to develope even better
solutions. Using Local Storage would be the next step to hold the information
between the pages, if needed this can be added.
TELLING YOUR STORY
This area showcases what we call Top Books which would utilize the person’s
own library of books that was entered in the use case. This area is calling up
genres for purchase based on the current history of the library.
